errataReason: This errata assessment has been created because the map was accidentally left out of the version published previously. Also, the use and trade information previously incorrectly stated that the species was hunted; this error was likely due to confusion with Glis glis.

Corrections have been made to three references cited in the text as follows:
  • Allen 1942 - reference to this has been deleted under Distribution, Population and Threats
  • Kienta 1982 - corrected to Kienta 1985 under Distribution, Population and Threats
  • Hill et al. 1988 - corrected to Grubb et al. 1988 under Distribution and Population.

assessor: Lovari, S., Lorenzini, R., Masseti, M., Pereladova, O., Carden, R.F., Brook, S.M. & Mattioli, S.
errataReason: This errata version of the assessment was created to attach the  corrected distribution map. The previous amended version of the 2015  assessment (which added two countries to the countries of occurrence  (Azerbaijan and Russian Federation), provided more details in the  'Geographic Range' section, and added an Assessor that was missing from  the previously published assessment) accidentally used the older version  of the map.

assessor: Lovari, S., Lorenzini, R., Masseti, M., Pereladova, O., Carden, R.F., Brook, S.M. & Mattioli, S.
errataReason: This errata version of the assessment was created to attach the  corrected distribution map. The previous amended version of the 2015  assessment (which added two countries to the countries of occurrence  (Azerbaijan and Russian Federation), provided more details in the  'Geographic Range' section, and added an Assessor that was missing from  the previously published assessment) accidentally used the older version  of the map.

The sentence A common denominator for all regions is that there is very law enforcement regarding the Marine Otter´s conservation status and protection, as hunting or killings on fish farms do not implicate consequences to the offenders. has been reworded to common denominator for all the range countries is the weak law enforcement in Marine otter conservation as hunting or killings of otters at fish farms do not implicate consequences to the offenders to correct a typing error in the original text.

The sentence Only six locations (some with multiple specimens) are known, all from museum collections before 1968 – apparently it has not been records since then. has been changed to Only six locations (some with multiple specimens) are known, all from museum collections before 1968 – apparently it has not been recorded since then. to correct a typo in records.

assessor: Bergl, R.A., Dunn, A., Fowler, A., Imong, I., Ndeloh, D., Nicholas, A. & Oates, J.F.
errataReason: This is an errata version of the 2016 assessment, correcting text in the Population section from "... the number of mature individuals is approximately 60% of the population (150-180; E.A. Williamson pers. comm. 2016)" to "... the number of mature individuals is approximately 60% of the population (150-180)".

assessor: Hearn, A., Ross, J., Brodie, J., Cheyne, S., Haidir, I.A., Loken, B., Mathai, J., Wilting, A. & McCarthy, J.
reviewer: Nowell, K., Hunter, L., Duckworth, J.W., Breitenmoser-Würsten, C., Lanz, T. & Breitenmoser, U.
errataReason: Added missing Bibliography references for Mathai et al. 2014,  Davis 1962,  and Nájera et al. in prep. which were cited in the text. Loken et al. in prep was corrected to Loken pers. comm. and Miettinen et al. 2010 was corrected to Miettinen et al. 2012.

assessor: Maisels, F., Strindberg, S., Greer, D., Jeffery, K., Morgan, D.L. & Sanz, C.
errataReason: This is an errata version of the 2016 assessment to correct some grammatical errors in the Threats section, and to remove the estimate of "140000" mature individuals: this figure includes juveniles and subadults along with mature animals; the percentage that are mature individuals is not known.

assessor: Glatston, A., Wei, F., Than Zaw & Sherpa, A.
errataReason: Corrected the spelling of an authors name used as a reference from Kendal, K., to Kandel, K., in the reference "Kendal, K., Huettmann, F., Krishna Suwal, M., Regmi, G.R., Nijman, V., Nekaris, K.A.I., Sonam Tashi Lama, Thapa, A., Sharma, H.P. and Subedi, T.R. 2015. Rapid multi-nation distribution assessment of a charismatic conservation species using open access ensemble model GIS predictions: Red Panda (Ailurus fulgens) in the Hindu-Kush Himalaya region. Biological Conservation 181: 150–161".

assessor: Brook, S.M., Pluháček, J., Lorenzini, R., Lovari, S., Masseti, M., Pereladova, O. & Mattioli, S.
errataReason: This errata version of the assessment was created to attached the  corrected distribution map. The previous amended version of the 2015  assessment (which provided more detail in the 'Geographic Range'  section,  added an Assessor that was missing from the previous  assessment (S.  Mattioli), and added New Zealand (introduced range) to  the countries of  occurrence) accidentally used the older version of the  map.

assessor: Ojeda, R., Bidau, C. & Emmons, L.
errataReason: This errata assessment has been created because the map was accidentally left out of the version published previously. In addition to these previous errata changes, a number of European countries have been added to the Countries of Occurrence table, that had previously been mentioned in the text.

assessor: Melovski, D., Breitenmoser, U., von Arx, M., Breitenmoser-Würsten, C. & Lanz, T.
errataReason: The Albanian Alps has different names in each of Kosovo (where it is known as 'Bjeshket e Nemuna'), Montenegro ('Prokletije') and Albania ('Albanian Alps'). Mention of 'Albanian Alps' in the Kosovo section of the Distribution text was therefore replaced with 'Bjeshket e Nemuna'.

assessor: Swaisgood, R., Wang, D. & Wei, F.
errataReason: Typo in the conservation actions section that read The Giant Panda has been the focus of none of the most intensive changed none to one.In addition to this change, a further type in the rational section which read they plant to continue investing has been changed to read they plan to continue investing.

assessor: Ndeloh, D., Maisels, F., Cronin, D.T. & Gadsby, E.
errataReason:
This errata version of the assessment was created to make the following corrections:
  • The assessment date was corrected from "2015-04-23" to "2018-03-08".
  • The assessor names were corrected from "Ndeloh, D., Maisels, F." to "Ndeloh, D., Maisels, F. Cronin, D.T., & Gadsby, E.L."
  • The reviewer name was corrected from "Schwitzer, C." to "Konstant, W."
  • One previously missing habitat was added: 4.7. Grassland -> Grassland - Subtropical/Tropical High Altitude

reviewer: Reeves, R., Taylor, B.L. & Braulik, G.
errataReason:
This errata version of the 2018 assessment was created to correct parts of the text in the Threats section:
  • Rates of hooking or entanglement are approximately 1.5 individuals for every 10 million hooks set is now corrected to Rates of hooking or entanglement are approximately 1.5 individuals for every 1 million hooks set.
  • Observers on Spanish longline vessels documented two bycaught False Killer Whales off the Azores in 2006 in approximately 810,000 observed hooks (Hernandez-Milian et al. 2008), a rate more than 15 times higher than in the Hawaii-based longline fishery is now corrected to Observers on Spanish longline vessels documented two bycaught False Killer Whales off the Azores in 2006 in approximately 810,000 observed hooks (Hernandez-Milian et al. 2008), a rate similar to the Hawaii-based longline fishery..

assessor: Cronin, D.T., Maisels, F., Ndeloh, D. & Gadsby, E.
errataReason:
This errata version of the assessment was created to fix the following errors and to update the distribution map for this species:
  • The assessment date was corrected from 2015-04-23 to 2018-03-08.
  • The names of the assessors were corrected from "Maisels, F. & Ndeloh, D." to "Cronin, D., Maisels, F., Ndeloh, D. & Gadsby, E.L."
  • The name of the reviewer was corrected from "Schwitzer, C." to "Konstant, W."
  • Two previously missing threats were added: 5.3.1. Biological resource use -> Logging & wood harvesting -> Intentional use: (subsistence/small scale) [harvest]; and 5.3.2. Biological resource use -> Logging & wood harvesting -> Intentional use: (large scale) [harvest].

assessor: de Jong, Y.A., Cumming, D., d'Huart, J. & Butynski, T.
errataReason: Corrected the title used in the reference Butynski, T.M. and De Jong, Y.A. In prep. Common Warthog (Phacochoerus africanus). In: M. Melletti and E. Meijaard (eds), Ecology, Evolution and Management of Wild Pigs and Peccaries. Implications for Conservation. So that it now correctly reads: Butynski, T.M. and De Jong, Y.A. In prep. Common Warthog (Phacochoerus africanus). In: M. Melletti and E. Meijaard (eds), Ecology, Conservation and Management of Wild Pigs and Peccaries. Cambridge University Press.

assessor: Wiles, G., Helgen, K. & Allison, A.
reviewer: Lamoreux, J. (Global Mammal Assessment Team), Racey, P.A., Medellín, R. & Hutson, A.M. (Chiroptera Red List Authority)
errataReason: This errata version of the 2008 assessment was created to correct the name of this taxon. Previously this appeared on The IUCN Red List as "Pteropus pelewensis_new ssp. yapensis"; this was a consequence of a new species concept for Pteropus pelewensis being created in the Red List database, which carried the temporary species level name through to the subspecies.

The original version of the 2015 assessment stated in the Habitats and Ecology section that "Monk Seals are known to eat more than 530 prey species"; this should have read "Monk Seals are known to eat more than 70 prey species". This errata version of the assessment corrects this statement.

assessor: van der Straeten, E., Decher, J., Corti, M. & Abdel-Rahman, E.H.
errataReason: This errata assessment has been created because the map was accidentally left out of the version published previously. A further errata version of this assessment has been created to correct the sentence This taxon has been recorded from Guinea-Bissau, Guinea, Sierra Leone, Ghana and Burkina Faso west to Ethiopia which should read This taxon has been recorded from Guinea-Bissau, Guinea, Sierra Leone, Ghana and Burkina Faso east to Ethiopia

reviewer: Festa-Bianchet, M. & Harris, R. (Caprinae Red List Authority)
errataReason: The Justification text mistakenly said that the species was listed as Vulnerable whereas it should have said Near Threatened. The reference for Tsalkin (1955) was missing from the Bibliography and has now been added. The formatting of the text was also corrected to comply with the IUCN Publications Standards.

assessor: Crespo, E., Olavarria, C., Dellabianca, N., Iñíguez, M., Ridoux, V. & Reeves, R.
errataReason: The original version of this assessment was published with an older version of the distribution map. This errata assessment uses the updated distribution map. In addition, a duplicate reference has been removed Bastida, R., Rodríguez, D. 2003. Mamíferos Marinos de Patagonia y Antártida. Vázquez Maziini Editores, Buenos Aires.

In the previous version of this assessment, the authors of the paper Status of the gray fox Lycalopex griseus (Gray, 1837) (Mammalia: Canidae) in Peru, were incorrectly spelt as "Pacheco, E. V. V. 2014" this has been corrected to "Vivar, E & Pacheco, V."

assessor: Bukhnikashvili, A., Kryštufek, B., Sozen, M., Yigit, N. & Amori, G.
amendedReason: This species was assessed under the name Spalax nehringi but it is now treated as Nannospalax xanthodon following Arslan et al. (2016). This amended assessment has been created for the taxonomic change.

assessor: Do Linh San, E., Gaubert, P., Wondmagegne, D. & Ray, J.
amendedReason: Occurrence of the species on Sao Tome Island was reported in the Geographic Range text originally, but it was not stated that this was as a result of an introduction and Sao Tome was not coded under the Countries of Occurrence. This amended version corrects these errors. The range map has not been updated to reflect the introduced range.

This species was assessed under the name Spalax leucodon but it is now treated under Nannospalax following Arslan et al. (2016). This amended assessment has been created for the taxonomic change and some other edits have been made to the genus and species names in the text and some spelling errors have been corrected.

In the previous published assessment Sudan was incorrectly recorded under the Countries of Occurrence that has now been corrected to South Sudan in this amended assessment. The range map was accidentally left out of the previous published version of this assessment and that omission is also corrected in this amended version.

This amended version of the assessment was created to correct the threat codes: the previous version of the assessment included threat code 5.3.2 (Biological resource use - Logging & wood harvesting - Intentional use: (large scale) [harvest]), which is not applicable to animals. The code was corrected to 5.3.4 (Biological resource use - Logging & wood harvesting - Unintentional effects: (large scale) [harvest]).

assessor: Stein, A.B., Athreya, V., Gerngross, P., Balme, G., Henschel, P., Karanth, U., Miquelle, D., Rostro-Garcia, S., Kamler, J.F., Laguardia, A., Khorozyan, I. & Ghoddousi, A.
reviewer: Nowell, K., Hunter, L., Duckworth, J.W., Breitenmoser-Würsten, C., Lanz, T. & Breitenmoser, U.
amendedReason: This is a slightly updated version of the amended version of the 2015 assessment, which was created for the 2019-3 Red List to update the distribution map for this species. The map was updated based on more recent data available from the Red List assessment for P. p. delacouri (Rostro-García et al. 2019, not Rostro-García et al. 2016 as previously noted). The reference for the more recent subspecies assessment has also been attached.

assessor: McDonald, R.A., Abramov, A.V., Stubbe, M., Herrero, J., Maran, T., Tikhonov, A., Cavallini, P., Kranz, A., Giannatos, G., Kry�tufek, B. & Reid, F.
amendedReason: Occurrence of the species on the Azores and Sao Tome Island were reported in the Geographic Range text originally but not coded under the Countries of Occurrence. This amended version corrects these errors. The range map has not been updated to reflect the introduced range.

assessor: McLellan, B.N., Proctor, M.F., Huber, D. & Michel, S.
amendedReason: The coding of the species' presence in Andorra, Austria, Czech Republic, and Turkmenistan was changed from "Certain" to "Uncertain" as bears are only occasionally present in these countries; likewise the presence in Switzerland was changed from "Reintroduced" to "Uncertain". Minor corrections have also been made to the text capitalizing the common names of species and correcting "population" to "subpopulation".

The spatial distribution and spatial data for this assessment are based on a paper published by Lewis, J.C., Powell, R.A. and Zielinski, W.J. 2012, but who were not cited in the paper as being the source of this data. A reference has now been included, and the spatial data for this assessment updated to reflect the correct source for this data.

assessor: Schlitter, D., Amori, G., Hutterer, R., Kryštufek, B., Yigit, N., Mitsain, G., Palomo, L.J. & Aulagnier, S
amendedReason: An errata version of this assessment was previously created to add the distribution map (which was accidentally omitted from the original version of this assessment). This amended version now corrects the spelling of the species name from mackillingini to mackilligini.
